Abstract: LOAN TO GOVERNMENT OF PARAGUAY SUPPORTS ENGINEERING AND CONSTRUCTION COSTS FOR REHABILITATION OF THE 327 KM 'BRAZIL ROAD', WHICH LINKS ASUNCION WITH PUNTO PRESIDENTE STROESSNER ON THE BRAZILIAN BORDER. ALONG SECTION A (73 KM) FROM ASUNCION TO EUSEBIO AYALA, SHOULDERS WILL BE REPAIRED; NEW CULVERTS AND DRAINS INSTALLED; HOLES AND EDGE FAILURES PATCHED; MINOR BASE FAILURES CORRECTED, AND DOUBLE COAT OF ASPHALT PLACED. EXTENSIVE ROAD FAILURES IN SECTION B (NEXT 59 KM TO CORONEL OVIEDO) REQUIRE VIRTUAL RECONSTRUCTION OF ROAD. ORIGINAL SURFACE AND BASE WILL BE REMOVED; BED GRADED; DRAINAGE INSTALLED; NEW DENSELY GRADED BASALT BASE PLACED; AND MULTIPLE-LIFT ASPHALT SURFACE APPLIED. SECTION C (NEXT 50 KM TO CAAGUAZU) REQUIRES INSTALLATION OF 4 PIPE CULVERTS; REMOVAL AND REPLACEMENT OF EXISTING SURFACE AND BASE (3 KM); REINFORCEMENT OF BASE WITH DENSE GRADED BASALT COURSE (50 KM); APPLICATION OF PRIME COAT (50 KM); AND SURFACING WITH MULTIPLE-LIFT ASPHALT (50 KM). FINAL 145 KM TO BRAZILIAN BORDER HAS HAD NO APPRECIABLE FAILURES, BUT, DUE TO TRAFFIC BY HEAVY LOGGING VEHICLES AND CONSTRUCTION EQUIPMENT, WILL REQUIRE REINFORCEMENT WITH MULTIPLE-LIFT SURFACE TO PREVENT FUTURE DETERIORATION. AS A CONDITION PRECEDENT TO DISBURSEMENT, GOP WILL DEVELOP A DETAILED PLAN FOR MAINTENANCE OF PROJECT HIGHWAY AND RELATED ROADS; ESTABLISH A REORGANIZED HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT, AND A ROAD MAINTENANCE UNIT WITHIN THAT DEPARTMENT; PROVIDE NECESSARY MAINTENANCE EQUIPMENT, TRAINING, AND PERSONNEL; AND ESTABLISH AND OPERATE VEHICLE WEIGHING STATIONS ALONG PROJECT ROAD. LINKING OF ASUNCION WITH BRAZILIAN HIGHWAY SYSTEM, AND THROUGH THAT SYSTEM TO THE FREE PORT AT PARANAGUA, WILL ELIMINATE NEED TO TRANSPORT INLAND FREIGHT BY RIVER. ESTABLISHMENT OF HIGH-SPEED TRUCK SERVICE WILL REDUCE COST OF IMPORTED GOODS, FACILITATE MARKETING OF EXPORT GOODS, AND ENCOURAGE SETTLEMENT AND DEVELOPMENT OF AREAS ALONG BRAZIL ROAD.

Abstract: LOAN PROVIDED TO BRAZIL'S STATE HIGHWAY DEPT OF SAO PAULO (DER)  TO UPGRADE ITS CAPACITY FOR MAINTAINING THE ROADS & HIGHWAYS UNDER ITS JURISDICTION. THIS PROJ IS ONE COMPONENT OF THE 1ST PHASE OF THE NATL HIGHWAY MAINTENANCE TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE PROGRAM (NHMP) -- AN AID/IBRD/GOB EFFORT TO CENTRALIZE BRAZILIAN HWY PLANNING RESPONSIBILITIES WHILE DECENTRALIZING HWY CONSTRUCTION/MAINTENANCE RESPONSIBILITIES. THIS LOAN ASSISTANCE TO DER TYPIFIES THAT TO BE PROVIDED TO OTHER BRAZILIAN STATE HWY DEPTS UNDER THE NHMP. LOAN WILL FUND ADDITIONAL & REPLAEMENT ROAD MAINT EQUPMNT AND THE TECH ASSISTANCE NECESSARY TO ALLOW THE DER TO CAPABLY ASSUME ALL MAINT RESPONSIBILITIES FOR EXISTING & PLANNED ROADS & HWYS WITHIN THE STATE BOUNDERIES. THESE RESPONSIBILITIES ARE PRESENTLY SHARED WITH THE NATL HWY DEPT (DNER), A GOB AGENCY WHICH IS BEING TRANSFORMED INTO STRICTLY A PLANNING & ADMIN UNIT UNDER THE RELATED PHASE I PROGRAM COMPONENT (512022901). THE MAJORITY OF THE LOAN (19 OUT OF THE $20 MILLION LOAN AMT)WILL BE USED FOR THE PROCUREMENT OF ROAD MAINT EQPMNT. THE REMAINDER WILL BE USED TO CONTRACT CONSULTING ENGINEERS TO WORK DIRECTLY WITH THE DER. FOR THE FIRST HALF OF THE PROJ IMPLEMENTATION PERIOD,CONSULTANTS WILL STUDY THE DER ORGANIZATIONAL & OPERATIONAL STRUCTURE TO DETERMINE THE REQUIREMENTS FOR DER REORGANIZATION. A COMPLETE PLAN FOR THIS REORG WILL THEREUPON BE FORMULATED. ALSO DURING THIS PERIOD,A TRAINING PROGRAM IN MAINT PROCEDURES (ENGINEERING DESIGN & SUPERVISION,DEVELOPMENT OF ROAD/HWY SPECIFICATIONS)AND THE PROPER USE OF MAINT EQPMNT WILL BE DEVELOPED FOR DER ENGINEERS,TECHNICIANS & EQPMNT OPERATORS. THE SECOND HALF OF PROJ IMPLEMENTATION WILL BE DEVOTED TO EXECUTING THE REORG REQUIREMENTS IDENTIFIED BY THE STUDY AND TRAINING PERSONNEL. THE DELIVERY OF NEW EQPMNT WILL BE DEPENDENT UPON THE PROPER ORGANIZATION OF DER'S MAINT YARDS,SHOPS,AND WAREHOUSES. EQPMNT PURCHASES WILL BE MADE FIRST FOR THE EXISTING ROAD NETWORD MAINT NEEDS; LATER PURCHASES WILL FOLLOW CONCOMITANTLY WITH NEW ROAD CONSTRUCTION.

Abstract: LOAN TO BOLIVIA'S EMPRESA NACIONAL DE ELECTRICIDAD (ENDE), AN AUTONOMOUS PUBLIC CORP THAT COORDINATES BOLIVIA'S ELECTRC GENRATN & TRANSMSSN, WILL FINANCE CONSTRCTN & EXPNSN OF ELECTRC POWR FACILS AT SANTA CRUZ & SEVRL TOWNS NORTH OF IT. ELECTRO-MECHANCL EQUIP WILL CONSIST OF 3 IDENTCL DUAL FUEL HEAVY DUTY DIESEL UNITS, EACH RATED 3300KW, USING ONLY GAS OR GAS & OIL COMBIND. NEARBY WELLS WILL SUPPLY WATER FOR COOLANT. GENRATN WILL PRODUCE 10KV 50 CYCLES, WITH 2 CIRCUITS CONNECTNG THE 10KV PLANT BUS WITH THE CITY DISTRIB SYSTM. A STEP-UP SUB-STATN AT THE PLANT WITH ONE 10MVA, 3-PHASE, 10KV/66KV TRANSFORMR WILL FEED THE SINGLE CIRCUIT TRANSMSSN LINE. TRANSMSSN LINE WILL BE A 66KV SINGLE CIRCUIT LINE ON IMPORTED STEEL STRUCTRS WITH A CONDUCTOR OF 266.8 MCM ACSR.WARNES & MONTERO WILL ECH HAVE A STEP-DOWN SUB-STATN WITH CAPACITIES OF 2 & 10MVA RESPECTVLY.EACH SUB-STATN WILL INCLUDE A SINGLE 3-PHASE TRANSFORMR.STEP-UP SUB-STATN WILL HAVE A MAIN & TRANSFR BUS,STEP-DOWN SUB-STATN WILL HAVE A SINGLE BUS.OUTDOOR METAL-CLAD SWITCHGEAR WILL BE PROVIDED FOR THE 24.9KV DISTRIB CIRCUITS,AS WELL AS CIRCUIT BREAKERS OF LOW OIL CONTENT WITH 250 MVA INTERRUPTING CAPACITY.NORMAL RELAY PROTECTION WILL BE PROVIDED FOR THE TRANSFORMERS & TRANSMISSION LINE. THE DISTRIBUTION SYSTEM IN SANTA CRUZ WILL OPERATE AT 10KV PRIMARY & 220/380V SECONDARY.BOTH URBAN & RURAL SYSTEMS WILL BE AERIAL,USING STEEL POLES IN SANTA CRUZ & ACSR CONDUCTOR.A FEW TABULAR STEEL POLES WILL BE REUSED.ENDE HAS AGREED WITH COOPERATIVA RURAL DE ELECTRICIDAD (CRE),A LOCAL COOP ORGANIZED IN ANTICIPATEON OF THIS LOAN,TO TRANSFER THE DISTRIBUTION SYSTEM TO CRE UPON COMPLETION.

Abstract: QUARTERLY REPORT FOR 4/1-6/30/66 BY UNIV OF WISCONSIN(UW) CONTRACTOR DESCRIBES ACTIVITIES & PROGRESS IN UW/USAID/UNIV OF RIC GRANDE DO SUL(URGS) COOP PROJ. OBJ OF PROJ IS TO SUCCESSFULLY ESTABLISH LAND GRANT COLLEGE CONEPT AT URGS THROUGH INSTIT REORGANIZATION AND UPGRADING OF FACULTY, CURRIC, & FACILITIES. ONLY 8 OF THE CONTRACT'S 13 POSITIONS ARE CURRENTLY FILLED. DESPITE ARRANGEMENTS IN PROGRESS,VACANCIES WILL LIKELY NOT BE FILLED PRIOR TO 1/1/67. WITH PROJ WORK RAPIDLY INCREASING & CURRENT STAFF SADDLED WITH CONTINUATION OF ACTIVITIES BEGUN BY OTHERS,STAFF SUBJECT TO HEAVY OVERLOAD. CONTRACT PROFESSORS ACTIVE IN THE DVLP OF GRAD PROGRAMS,TEACHING OF GRAD COURSES,AND ADVISING OF STUDENTS & GUIDANCE OF THIER THESIS WORK. 8 FARMS IDENTIFIED ON WHICH STUDENTS CAN RECEIVE FIELD EXPERIENCE. SUBPROJS CONTINUING WITH ADV ASSISTANCE OF CONTRACT PROJS INCLUDE: (1)COMMUNICATION & CREDIT PROJ,MEASURING FLOW OF INFO FROM CREDIT INSTIT TO FARMER-USERS; DATA ANALYSIS OF INTERVIEW RESULTS BEGUN; (2)LEADERSHIP IN RURAL DVLP COOP PROJ WIITH STATE EXTENSION SERVICE; QUESTIONAIRES BEING DESIGNED; (3)CREDIT SATURATION STUDY; AWAITING BANCO CENTRA1 APPROPRIATION OF FUNDS. DAIRY FARM PRACTICES STUDY HAS BEEM COMPLETED. NEWLY PROPOSED ARE STUDY TO DETERMINE EDUC NEEDS OF AGRIC INSTRUCTORS & PROJ ON ECON/SOCIAL FACTORS AFFECTING AGRIC PRODUCTIVITY CHANGES. SEMINARS HAVE BEEN CONDUCTED FOR AGRIC TECH WORKERS. NATL VOACTIONAL AGRIC OFFICE BEING ASSISTED IN DVLP OF ADULT FARMER COURSES & VOC AGRIC SCHOOL CURRIC. MONTENEGRO EXPERIMENT STATION,DEVELOPED & EQUIPPED AS RESULT OF PROJ,RECOGNIZED THROUGHOUT REGION FOR ITS RESEARCH POTENTIAL. PROJ HAS DEMONSTRATED INCREASED CORN,FORAGE,& SOYBEAN YEILDS DESPITE RECENT CROP DAMAGE DUE TO HIGH TEMPERATURES/LACK OF RAINFALL. LATE ARRIVAL OF FERTILIZER & SEED CAUSED DELAY OF FORAGE DEMO PROJ. STUDY HAS DEMONSTRATED FEASIBILITY OF MAJOR TEMPERATE CLIMATE FRUIT INDUSTRY. INSTIT REORGANIZATION AT URGS PROGRESSING WITH PLANNED RESTRUCTURING OF FACULTY OF AGRONOMY/VETERINARY,SOIL INSTITUTE & INST OF FORAGES/ANIMAL NUTR. PROJ HAS RECEIVED BRAZILIAN FUNDS SLOWLY,BUT SUPPLM SUPPORT FOR RES/EXTEN FROM BRAZILIAN AGENCIES.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 1 APR 1966-30 JUN 1966

Abstract: PROJECT TO DEVELOP AN EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS PRODUCTION AND DISTRIBUTION NETWORK IN LATIN AMERICA IS EVALUATED FOR THE PERIOD 7/1/57 TO 2/28/66. AUDIT WAS COMPILED THROUGH A REVIEW OF ALLOTMENT AND PROJECT LEDGERS, EXAMINATION OF ACCOUNTING AND RECORDING PROCEDURES, AND INSPECTION OF THE WAREHOUSE. IT FOCUSES ON PROCUREMENT PROCEDURES. CONTRACTING PROCEDURES FOR BOTH COMMERCIAL AND NON-COMMERCIAL PROCUREMENT ARE JUDGED EXTREMELY WEAK. UNSOUND CONTRACTING PRACTICES WHICH WERE UTILIZED INCLUDE; 1)PLACING OF ONE EMPLOYEE IN A POSITION OF TOTAL CONTROL OVER PROCUREMENT; 2)PREDETERMINING CONTRACTOR SELECTION BY USING WEIGHTED CLASSIFICATION OF CONTRACTOR GROUPS; 3)ACCEPTING INCOMPLETE DOCUMENTATION FROM PROSPECTIVE SUPPLIERS; 4)PLACING MANY BADLY QUALIFIED SUPPLIERS, WHO HAD INADEQUATE FACILITIES ON THE PRE-SELECTED LIST; AND 5)OMITTING THE CONTROL PROCEDURE OF COMPARING SUPPLIER BIDS AGAINST INTERNALLY COMPUTED COST ESTIMATES. THE FOLLOWING RECOMMENDATIONS ARE INCLUDED; 1)THE REGIONAL TECHNICAL AIDS CENTER (RTAC) SHOULD ESTABLISH CONTRACT PROCEDURES REFLECTIVE OF FEDERAL PROCUREMENT REGULATIONS AND AID PROCUREMENT POLICY; 2)A TIME AND PROCEDURAL STUDY SHOULD BE CONDUCTED TO DETERMINE THE POSSIBILITY OF LEVELING WORKLOAD; 3)THE WAREHOUSE AND INVENTORY CONTROL CONTRACT SHOULD BE REVIEWED FOR PROPRIETY, AND SUCH CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN AS CONDITIONS DICTATE, 4)THE WAREHOUSE AND INVENTORY CONTROL CONTRACTOR SHOULD BE NOTIFIED THAT HE HAS NOT MET THE COVENANT OF RESPONSIBILITY UNDER THE CONTRACT, AND THAT THE AGREEMENT WILL BE TERMINATED WITHIN THE TIME ALLOWED BY THE CONTRACT, IF ADEQUATE INSURANCE ON INVENTORIES IS NOT PROMPTLY PROVIDED; AND 5)RTAC SHOULD FOLLOW PRESCRIBED CONTRACTING PROCEDURES, OR ADEQUATELY JUSTIFY AND DOCUMENT ANY DEPARTURES FROM THESE STANDARDS. PROCUREMENT SHOULD NOT BE APPROVED PRIOR TO SUCH JUSTIFICATION.

Abstract: Frequently, distinguished visitors and new employees of the U.S Country Team in Iran have a need for highly condensed Information on the activities of the Agency for International Development in Iran.  The following pages were designed to fulfill this need.  They contain summary information about the current operations of the USAID Mission to Iran and highlights of the extensive A.I.D. economic assistance program between 1950 and the present time.  The text material is supplemented with appendices containing some of the more significant facts and figures.  Necessarily, a comprehensive treatment of the USAID Mission's current and past operations in Iran will not be found in this brief booklet.  Further, no attempt has been made to recapitulate the considerable Iranian effort, which is a story in itself.  The aim of this publication is merely to provide enough information from both the past and the present to give the busy reader a quick "birds eye" view of the A.I.D. effort.  Supplemental material is, of course, available for those interested In more complete details of the Mission's activities. (Author abstract)

Abstract: Evaluates project performance from 2/63 to 2/66 in Nigeria. USAID involvement consists of a contract with New York University (NYU) to assist in establishing a Faculty of Business and Commerce within the new University of Lagos. Encouraging progress was made from 10/62 to the beginning of the crisis at the University in 2/65 over selection of a new Vice-Chancellor. The crisis had serious impact on NYU activities, stopping completely much of the progress underway. Total faculty for the new School of Business grew quickly from 5 in 10/62 to 15 at the start of the 1964-65 academic year. These figures include 2 NYU faculty members in 1962, 3 in 1963, and 4 in 1964. Originally, the Faculty of Business was to offer degree programs in business administration, public administration, and accounting, with support courses in economics and general studies.  Shortly after the school opened, however, students protested the absence of certain traditional and coveted major specializations such as economics and political science.  Hence, the public administration specialization was eliminated in favor of political science, and economics was elevated to a full-fledged major. These organizational adjustments were reflected in a new name for the faculty:  the Faculty of Business and Social Studies. Student enrollment in the Faculty grew from 46 in 1962 to 290 in the Fall of 1965 which is remarkably close to the 300 projected by NYU. NYU staff conducted a research program resulting in many useful classroom materials with case studies reflecting actual business situations in Nigeria.  NYU introduced other new teaching techniques such as field trips and special lectures by businessmen. The university crisis reduced the NYU team to 3.  A large number of Nigerian faculty also resigned and the university had to be closed on 3/4/65.  When the University was reopened in 10/65, the issue of continued US assistance and NYU's role remained unresolved. The report describes the conflicts which may arise from having a contractor being responsible to both USAID and, at the same time, function operationally under the authority of the host university.

Abstract: LOAN PROVIDED TO THE GOVERNMENT OF HONDURAS (GOH) TO STRENGTHEN ITS ECONOMIC PROGRAMS, ADMINISTRATIVE PLANNING, AND RURAL DEVELOPMENT CAPABILITIES. THE LOAN WILL FINANCE SECTORAL OR RESOURCE SURVEYS, PREFEASIBILITY-FEASIBILITY STUDIES OF GOVERNMENT-EXECUTED INFRASTRUCTURE PROJECTS AND PRIVATE SECTOR INVESTMENT PROPOSALS. MOST OF THE FUNDS WILL BE USED FOR FEASIBILITY STUDIES OF SUCH INFRASTRUCTURE ACTIVITIES AS ROADS, IRRIGATION, GROUND WATER RESOURCES DEVELOPMENT, AND PRIVATE INDUSTRIALIZATION. WITHIN EACH MAJOR CATEGORY, FEASIBILITY STUDIES WILL BE CONDUCTED ON THE DEVELOPMENT OF ACCESS AND SECONDARY ROADS, WELLS, WINDMILLS, DRAINAGE SYSTEMS, AND IRRIGATION DISTRICTS. INFORMATION CONTAINED IN THESE STUDIES WILL OUTLINE VIRTUALLY ALL ELEMENTS OF A PROJECT DESIGN PAPER. THE NEC WILL EVALUATE REQUESTS FOR FEASIBILITY STUDIES SUBMITTED BY VARIOUS GOH MINISTRIES AND WILL PRESENT PRIORITY REQUESTS TO USAID FOR APPROVAL AND FUNDING. USAID WILL REVIEW THE STUDIES AND CONTRACTS FOR PROJECT FUNDING TO ENSURE THAT THE PROPOSED DEVELOPMENT PROJECT IS OF HIGH PRIORITY TO HONDURAS' DEVELOPMENT, AND THAT THERE IS SERIOUS GOH INTENT TO FUND THE PROJECT. EFFORTS WILL BE MADE TO ESTABLISH A REVOLVING FUND TO FINANCE FUTURE FEASIBILITY STUDIES, CREATED BY REQUIRING LENDERS TO INCLUDE THE COST OF THE STUDY IN THE OVERALL PROJECT COST. AN AMENDMENT TO THE CAPITAL ASSISTANCE PAPER, DATED APRIL 11, 1969, RECOMMENDS INCREASING THE ORIGINAL LOAN OF $500,000 TO $1,000,000. IT THEREBY INCREASES FUNDS FOR EXISTING FEASIBILITY STUDY CATEGORIES, AND PROVIDES FUNDS FOR NATURAL RESOURCE SURVEYS AND FOR STUDIES ON FOREST PRODUCTS, FOUNDRIES AND METAL WORKING, AND TOURISM. SOMETIME BETWEEN PROJECT IMPLEMENTATION IN 1966 AND THE 1969 AMENDMENT, THE NEC WAS REORGANIZED AND RENAMED THE SUPERIOR COUNCIL FOR ECONOMIC PLANNING.
